{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413065"},"attributes":{"position":1,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:53:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:53:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12331"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514562"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:23:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12331"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"12331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12331"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.4,0.1,0.37,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4851"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58777"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4851"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12331"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44183"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"682"},{"type":"tags","id":"765"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7834"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8431"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18319"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58777"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old woman is brought into the Emergency Department after being stabbed in the abdomen. She is complaining of pain in her right upper quadrant. On examination there is a single deep laceration in the right upper quadrant, consistent with a knife wound. There is localised tenderness and the rest of the abdomen is soft. Her blood pressure is 110/80 mmHg, pulse 108/min and temperature 37.6\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. A CT scan is performed and the arterial phase shows an active arterial blush. A portal venous phase film is shown (Image),\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Close observation in HDU","Emergency laparotomy","Percutaneous drainage","Angioembolisation","Blood transfusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ELiver trauma is usually classified using the AAST grading scale (Image). The patient has presented with grade III trauma according to this scale. The patient is haemodynamically stable but there is extravasation and a collection of blood within the parenchyma as shown on the CT. In addition, the blush shows active arterial bleeding and this needs to be treated. Liver trauma of lower grades are usually treated non-operatively when the patient is haemodynamically stable. \u003Cstrong\u003EAngioembolisation\u003C/strong\u003E is utilised when the patient presents with lower-grade liver trauma, is haemodynamically stable and when there is a demonstration of active extravasation of blood. The term angioembolisation describes arterial catheterisation, followed by radiographic identification of the site of the bleeding and occlusion (embolus) of the vessel directly feeding the bleeding point.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClose observation in HCU \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be indicated in lower-grade liver trauma (AAST I and II) with blunt or stab injury when the patient is haemodynamically stable and there is no evidence of extravasation of blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous drainage\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated in certain cases of hepatic trauma, such as those involving fluid collections or abscesses. Percutaneous drainage is generally recommended for patients with AAST grade I-III injuries, who are clinically stable, without evidence of ongoing bleeding, and who have a fluid collection or abscess that is accessible by percutaneous means. The procedure is typically performed under imaging guidance, such as ultrasound or CT, to ensure accurate placement of the drainage catheter.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmergency laparotomy \u003C/strong\u003Eis indicated as an initial management option when the patient is hemodynamically unstable and has signs and symptoms of massive haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood transfusion \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be necessary for this patient because she is haemodynamically stable and there are no signs of massive haemorrhage that could have led to signs and symptoms of shock, necessitating blood transfusion,\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lower-grade liver injuries with extravasation of blood when the patient is haemodynamically stable are managed with angioembolisation."],"references":["Taghavi S, Askari R. Liver Trauma. [Updated 2022 Jul 19]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Ahmed N, Vernick JJ. Management of liver trauma in adults. J Emerg Trauma Shock. 2011 Jan;4(1):114-9. doi: 10.4103/0974-2700.76846. PMID: 21633579; PMCID: PMC3097559."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44183"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12331"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19561"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19562"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19561"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/71394ceb-d55d-4e8e-bbbd-fe5b14ba6e16.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/71394ceb-d55d-4e8e-bbbd-fe5b14ba6e16.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":582,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"19562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19562"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4158a56d-d3cb-4964-b18b-86df1234f1cc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4158a56d-d3cb-4964-b18b-86df1234f1cc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1500}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44183"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-02T18:46:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-02T18:47:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4851"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58777"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updat